        "Short Hypothesis": "While multi-modal machine learning is widely adopted, we hypothesize that for classifying Type 2 Diabetes progression across distinct clinical stages using a diverse, real-world dataset (ECG, CGM, retinal imaging, environmental, and clinical data), the incremental performance gains of multi-modal fusion over well-engineered unimodal models may be marginal or dataset-dependent, especially in settings with limited patient numbers. This specific direction is crucial because the perceived superiority of multi-modal approaches often leads to increased model complexity without rigorous justification of actual clinical benefit over simpler alternatives. There are no simpler ways to answer this question than by systematically comparing unimodal and multi-modal classification performance on a rich, multi-modal dataset like AI-READI.",
        "Related Work": "Existing literature extensively explores multi-modal machine learning for disease diagnosis and prognosis. For instance, Matboli et al. (2025) applied ML for diabetes stratification using molecular and biochemical markers, demonstrating the potential of multi-class classification. Chappidi et al. (2025) developed interpretable multi-modal algorithms for glioblastoma progression using imaging, NLP, and clinical data. Other works (e.g., Talsania & Modi, 2026; Pothireddy et al., 2026) focus on novel fusion strategies or general frameworks. However, a critical gap remains: few studies rigorously quantify the *incremental value* of multi-modal fusion compared to strong, carefully optimized unimodal baselines, especially in a context like Type 2 Diabetes progression where diverse, high-dimensional, and often noisy data modalities (ECG, CGM, retinal images) are combined with structured clinical data. This proposal distinguishes itself by directly challenging the implicit assumption that 'more modalities are always better,' instead focusing on a head-to-head empirical comparison to understand *when* and *by how much* multi-modal fusion genuinely improves classification performance for diabetes progression, considering the practical implications of increased model complexity and data integration challenges. We aim to identify scenarios where simpler unimodal models might be sufficient or even preferred.",
        "Abstract": "The AI-READI project provides a unique multi-modal dataset for Type 2 Diabetes (T2DM) research, encompassing cardiac ECG, continuous glucose monitoring (CGM), retinal imaging, environmental sensors, and structured clinical records across four distinct progression stages: healthy, pre-diabetes, oral medication-controlled, and insulin-dependent. Despite the growing trend towards multi-modal machine learning in healthcare, the actual incremental benefit of integrating diverse data streams over robust unimodal approaches remains underexplored, particularly in real-world clinical datasets with inherent complexities and limited sample sizes. This research rigorously investigates whether combining cardiac, metabolic, retinal, environmental, and clinical biomarkers significantly enhances the classification of diabetes progression stages compared to utilizing any single modality alone. We will develop and evaluate both unimodal models (e.g., ECG-only, CGM-only, clinical-only) and various multi-modal fusion strategies (e.g., early, late, and hybrid fusion) for distinguishing between the four progression groups. Through a systematic comparison using balanced accuracy, F1-score, and AUC, we aim to quantify the performance gains, if any, of multi-modal approaches. The study will also explore feature importance within each modality to understand their individual contributions. By critically assessing the utility of multi-modal fusion, this work seeks to provide actionable insights into the effective design of predictive models for T2DM progression, addressing whether the added complexity genuinely translates into superior clinical utility or if simpler models offer comparable performance.",
