        "Short Hypothesis": "We hypothesize that Type 2 Diabetes (T2DM) progression, as currently categorized by clinical stages, may mask significant underlying biological heterogeneity. Through multi-modal unsupervised learning on diverse physiological (ECG, CGM), imaging (retinal), environmental, and clinical data from the AI-READI dataset, we can discover novel, data-driven patient sub-phenotypes that offer a more nuanced understanding of disease mechanisms and potentially predict differential progression or treatment response than existing clinical classifications. This specific direction is crucial because it moves beyond merely classifying predefined stages to *discovering* new, potentially more biologically meaningful disease stratifications, which is essential for personalized medicine. There are no simpler ways to answer this question; it requires integrating and analyzing complex, heterogeneous data in an unsupervised manner to uncover hidden structures.",
        "Related Work": "Existing literature acknowledges the heterogeneity of Type 2 Diabetes (T2DM) and its progression. Some studies, like Udler et al. (2018), have used multi-trait genetic data to cluster T2D loci and identify disease mechanisms and subtypes, demonstrating the power of multi-modal approaches for sub-phenotype discovery. Similarly, Saoi et al. (2020) applied unsupervised methods to serum biomarkers to identify distinct sub-groups in non-alcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH) with similar clinical presentations. While these works highlight the potential of unsupervised multi-modal analysis in related metabolic diseases, our proposal distinguishes itself by focusing on a rich combination of *dynamic physiological time-series (ECG, CGM), imaging (retinal scans), and environmental sensor data*, alongside traditional clinical records, to uncover sub-phenotypes of T2DM progression. Unlike previous work that might focus on genetic or biochemical markers, we leverage real-time, high-dimensional data streams that capture ongoing physiological processes. This moves beyond 'classification into known groups' (as in our previous proposal) to 'discovery of novel, data-driven groups,' offering a fundamentally different contribution to understanding T2DM heterogeneity, particularly in a cohort with distinct clinical progression stages.",
        "Abstract": "Type 2 Diabetes (T2DM) is a highly heterogeneous disease, yet clinical staging often relies on simplified categories that may not fully capture its underlying biological diversity. The AI-READI dataset, with its rich multi-modal data spanning cardiac ECG, continuous glucose monitoring (CGM), retinal imaging, environmental sensors, and structured clinical records across four progression stages (healthy, pre-diabetes, oral medication-controlled, insulin-dependent), presents a unique opportunity to explore this heterogeneity. This research proposes to move beyond supervised classification of known stages and instead employ multi-modal unsupervised learning to discover novel patient sub-phenotypes within or across these established clinical groups. We hypothesize that by integrating and jointly analyzing these diverse data streams, we can uncover distinct biological clusters of T2DM progression that are not apparent from single-modality or traditional clinical assessments. We will leverage advanced multi-modal representation learning techniques (e.g., deep autoencoders, contrastive learning) followed by robust clustering algorithms to identify these sub-phenotypes. Subsequent analysis will characterize the discovered clusters based on their defining features from each modality and assess their clinical relevance by comparing them to the existing clinical progression groups and exploring potential differential clinical implications. This work aims to provide a more granular understanding of T2DM pathophysiology, potentially paving the way for personalized diagnostics and treatment strategies.",
