        "Name": "interpretable_multimodal_biomarkers_diabetes",
        "Title": "Unpacking the Black Box: Interpretable Multi-Modal Biomarker Shifts Across Diabetes Progression Stages",
        "Short Hypothesis": "We hypothesize that employing intrinsically interpretable multi-modal machine learning architectures will enable us to identify and quantify the dynamic, stage-specific contributions of features from cardiac (ECG), metabolic (CGM), retinal, environmental, and clinical data in distinguishing *each transition* between Type 2 Diabetes progression stages (e.g., Healthy vs. Pre-diabetes, Pre-diabetes vs. Medication-controlled, etc.). This specific direction is crucial because it moves beyond merely predicting progression or identifying overall important features to providing a granular, mechanistic understanding of *which physiological signals become most diagnostic at what point* in the disease continuum, offering targeted insights for early detection and intervention. There are no simpler ways to answer this question; it requires a multi-modal framework designed for interpretability that can analyze differential feature importance across clinically defined stages.",
        "Related Work": "The existing literature extensively leverages multi-modal data for diabetes-related predictions (e.g., diabetes risk forecasting [Sidhu et al., 2025], fibrosis progression in NAFLD [Meng et al., 2023], diabetic foot progression [Chen et al., 2025]), often incorporating post-hoc interpretability techniques like SHAP [An et al., 2024; OAAgent, Ahadian et al., 2025]. Some frameworks, like IMML [Nguyen et al., 2024], aim for interpretability by integrating prior biological knowledge or focusing on biomarker identification. Our previous proposals explored the *utility* of multi-modal fusion for classification and the *discovery* of sub-phenotypes or *inter-modal discordances*. This proposal distinguishes itself by focusing on the *dynamic, stage-specific interpretability* of multi-modal contributions to diabetes progression. Instead of asking 'what features are important overall?' or 'how do modalities relate generally?', we ask: 'Which *specific features* from *which modalities* become most salient and diagnostic *at each specific transition point* in diabetes progression (e.g., distinguishing healthy from pre-diabetes, versus distinguishing medication-controlled from insulin-dependent)?' This requires not just an interpretable model, but one designed to reveal *differential* feature importance across consecutive progression stages. This provides a fine-grained understanding of the evolving physiological signatures of T2DM, moving beyond aggregate importance to a progression-aware, actionable interpretability.",
